      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "827423d3de9c10b37b46eeae9f3799a9823c4e57",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 125,
        "name": "James Simmons",
        "email": "jsimmons@infradead.org",
        "username": "jsimmons"
      },
      "date": "2018-12-14 00:10:39.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\nI will create a reasonable patch",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "da04e5f7cf1951fa17ded9ca7066dae4db388b87",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 117,
        "name": "Andreas Dilger",
        "email": "adilger@thelustrecollective.com",
        "username": "adilger"
      },
      "date": "2018-12-14 03:24:52.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\n(1 comment)\n\n> I see the problem. jiffies is initialized to five minutes before boot time.\n> Another reason I hate jiffies.\n\nThat is done on purpose, to catch driver bugs early on instead of only after 49 days.  However, if Lustre isn't mounted in the first 5 minutes after boot, or doesn't hit this code at the right time it may not hit that particular bug.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "f1d23ce56bdcb5e9760d05d04011a57272d91a28",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 125,
        "name": "James Simmons",
        "email": "jsimmons@infradead.org",
        "username": "jsimmons"
      },
      "date": "2018-12-15 15:34:58.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\nI am working on this. Currently I'm doing a study of the kernel time code to make sure I do this right. The complexity here is that the code handles the real time clock in seconds, obd_recovery_start for exmaple, timeouts in seconds and then work with jiffies due to the timer. I'm working on a way to streamline all this which I started to play with these ideas in the last LU-9019 patch.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "d83b4627a8fada3fb85ff01290edefafede5a358",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 117,
        "name": "Andreas Dilger",
        "email": "adilger@thelustrecollective.com",
        "username": "adilger"
      },
      "date": "2018-12-15 18:57:08.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\n> The complexity here is that the code handles the real time clock\n > in seconds, obd_recovery_start for exmaple, timeouts in seconds\n > and then work with jiffies due to the timer.\n\nI did a look through the code, and I don't see where obd_recovery_start interacts directly with obd_recovery_timer?  It looks like obd_recovery_start is mostly used for printing messages to the console/lprocfs.  I'm fine with _just_ fixing the use of obd_recovery_timer in this patch to use jiffies, and leave other cleanups to other patches.\n\nOther places I saw that need some help:\n- obd_t10_performance_test() and cfs_crypto_performance_test() are using msecs_to_jiffies(MSEC_PER_SEC / 4), but msecs_to_jiffies() converts to a static inline function that directly uses HZ for kernel > 4.1.  These should be using __msecs_to_jiffies() if available or add a __msecs_to_jiffies() compat macro for older kernels.\n- LNetCtl(), lnet_ping(), lnet_sock_write(), lnet_sock_read(), target_recovery_overseer(), __ldlm_namespace_free(), __lfsck_set_speed(), lfsck_start_all(), ll_kill_super(), ll_statahead_thread(), ... are also using msecs_to_jiffies() and should be fixed as above.\n- brw_stats_show() is using jiffies_to_msecs(1000) / MSEC_PER_SEC, but that is wrong for multiple reasons.  I already have a patch for this.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
